			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I found this an interesting analysis on Bush's proposed SS reform:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">“Privatizing Social Security” really means federalizing the bond and stock markets.
<br />

<br />
Probably the most detailed source on what President Bush would like to do with Social Security can be found in the President's Commission to Strengthen Social Security ( <a href="http://www.csss.gov/reports/Final_report.pdf)." target="_blank">www.csss.gov/reports/Final_report.pdf).</a> That report begins with a key principle: “The government must not invest Social Security funds in the stock market.”
<br />

<br />
However, the report provides three alternative plans that rely on mutual funds that do invest in the stock market. A careful reading of those plans shows already that personal accounts will be restricted with respect to the frequency with which funds can be transferred, the kinds of investments that will be allowed and the way that funds can be withdrawn. Furthermore, a board will be set up to decide what further restrictions might be necessary.
<br />

<br />
Choice will be much more restricted than what can currently be found even in 401(k) and other government-sponsored savings plans. Such restrictions can be expected to open a future lobbying frenzy by companies that want the new board to include their investment instruments and by recipients who want better returns.
<br />

<br />
In a kindhearted attempt to guarantee safety, the board will create a two-tier market of investments — those that are deemed safe and permissible and those that are not.
<br />

<br />
The risky startup companies, upon whom this economy depends to pull itself out recession, will most likely be placed on the nonpermitted list. The entrepreneurs who need funding for new inventions, upon which this economy depends for growth and greater productivity, will also most likely be placed on the nonpermitted list.
<br />

<br />
However, when the economy enters a recession, the new board will have a very strong reason to prop up the firms on the permitted list — it won't want to face retirees who have lost their holdings. If a depression wipes out those holdings, will the government allow people to starve because they made bad investment decisions for their personal accounts?
<br />

<br />
Probably not.
<br />

<br />
In other words, not only will the government have more incentive to tamper with the stock market, but taxpayers will have to pay three times to have their Social Security:
<br />

<br />
• Once to pay the benefits already promised to those already on Social Security.
<br />

<br />
• Once to subsidize their stock market losses in their personal accounts.
<br />

<br />
• Once to re-establish the Social Security system as it is today after personal accounts have failed.
<br />

<br />
The shocks from each change in policy may themselves destabilize the stock market.
<br />

<br />
Since extra funding cannot be achieved by raising taxes alone, the funding of personal accounts must be financed with more government debt. That greater debt, which will amount to a trillion dollars or more, will result in a serious crowding-out of private debt with resultant rises in interest rates for the whole economy.
<br />

<br />
All of these reasons mean that privatizing Social Security is really about federalizing the bond and stock markets — the government will be responsible for stabilizing them even as it adds to their instability.
<br />

<br />
There is at least one silver lining to the private accounts. Interest rates will go up on government bonds due to the added debt requirements to fund the transition to personal accounts. Workers will be able to choose funds that invest in the government bonds and receive higher returns for their retirement. The bad news is that their children will have to pay the higher interest through higher taxes.
<br />

<br />
Michael Tansey is a professor of economics at Rockhurst University.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.kansascity.com/mld/kansascity/business/11370050.htm" target="_blank">http://www.kansascity.com/mld/kansascity/business/11370050.htm</a>
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"><br />
