An income based tax never touches the rich nor the poor.  It is the middle class that it targets.  It cannot be structured otherwise.  The rich do not have incomes if they do not want them.  They ride around in helicopters and limos that are owned by a corporation and live on business expenses. Other countries will be glad to have them live and keep their wealth there.  If the rich are taxed they move where they are not. There is little we can do about it.
<br />

<br />
We could track every penny but we still could not avoid this factor without also refusing people the right to expatriate; we could only allow citizens to participate in business here; also, we would also need to be able to enforce the rule (including having the same tracking of every penny) on all markets that interfaced with ours.
<br />

<br />
Since you "have to tax" to raise funds,  you do it on goods and services in the raw transaction.  This becomes a problem to the middle class again if you do it at every transaction level so it is best to do it at one end or the other so that everyone pays. Supply side is the easiest to track and the least invasive to rights.  If you were to cut it down to ONLY tarriffs on imports... You would then have original constitutional design.
<br />

<br />
Problem is that taxes are a social engineering tool and fascism still runs deep in our social mind.  People presume that the governnment is there to steer society. To me this seems opposite to design.<br />
